<a class="zemanta-img alignleft" href="http://www.amazon.com/Myth-Rational-Market-History-Delusion/dp/0060598999%3FSubscriptionId%3D0G81C5DAZ03ZR9WH9X82%26tag%3Dzem-20%26linkCode%3Dxm2%26camp%3D2025%26creative%3D165953%26creativeASIN%3D0060598999" target="_blank"><img class="zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured" title="Cover of &quot;The Myth of the Rational Market..." alt="Cover of &quot;The Myth of the Rational Market..." src="http://ecx.images-amazon.com/images/I/51B8R5z84mL._SL300_.jpg" width="141" height="204" /></a>

&nbsp;

<a title="The Myth of the Rational Market: Wall Street's Impossible Quest for Predictable Markets" href="http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/4749235-the-myth-of-the-rational-market">The Myth of the Rational Market: Wall Street's Impossible Quest for Predictable Markets </a>by <a class="zem_slink" title="Justin Fox" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Justin_Fox" target="_blank" rel="wikipedia">Justin Fox</a>- This is a review of the history of <a class="zem_slink" title="Efficient-market hypothesis" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Efficient-market_hypothesis" target="_blank" rel="wikipedia">efficient market</a> theories and an introduction to some counter points raised in recent years. It is very accessible to non-economists and has got off to an interesting start. More will come later.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

<a class="zemanta-img alignleft" href="http://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Israel_Kirzner.jpg" target="_blank"><img class="zemanta-img-inserted zemanta-img-configured" title="Israel Kirzner, Austrian School economist" alt="Israel Kirzner, Austrian School economist" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d4/Israel_Kirzner.jpg" width="170" height="225" /></a>

<a title="Competition and Entrepreneurship" href="http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1084282.Competition_and_Entrepreneurship">Competition and Entrepreneurship </a>by <a class="zem_slink" title="Israel Kirzner" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Israel_Kirzner" target="_blank" rel="wikipedia">Israel Kirzner</a>- This is my second run though of Dr. Kirzner's famous work. At times, astonishingly convincing, at times a little more difficult to follow, it is always insightful. Whether his theory is complete is not for me to say, but he does add a nice dimension to disequilibrium to the microeconomic equilibrium analysis that dominated the time of Kirzner's writing. I hope to do either a full length review or a chapter by chapter analysis for my own records.

